For ER network (homogeneous):
- R₀ = β/γ × 〈k〉 (here, ≈2.5 with β=1.1, γ=0.43, 〈k〉=10);
- Threshold: R₀ > 1, i.e., epidemic requires sufficient average degree or transmissibility;
- Final epidemic size: r_∞ ≈ 1 – exp(–R₀ × r_∞).
For scale-free/heterogeneous network:
- R₀ = β/γ × (〈k²〉–〈k〉)/〈k〉; for γ∈[2,3] and large N, 〈k²〉→∞, so threshold vanishes (even low T sufficient for epidemic spread);
- Final size: use self-consistency with generating functions of degree distribution (G₁(u)=u, r_∞=1–G₀(u)).
Thus, heterogeneous networks permit more frequent/larger outbreaks at lower β; ER networks retain a classical finite threshold.
